<MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">
    Resolving Skill Rolls
</MudText>

<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
    When a Skill Check is called, you roll a Base Die and a Proficiency Die corresponding to your proficiency in that Skill.
    <br />
    <br />
    <b>Final result of a Skill Check is the sum of Base Die and the Proficiency Die that you rolled for that check.</b>
    <br />
    <br />
    In order to ascertain whether the Skill Check was successful, the GM decides whether the roll was made as part of a Contested Check or Against Difficulty Rating.
    <br />
    <br />
    Contested Check means that two different characters made Skill Checks opposing each other (for example, trying to push each other), and it is considered that whoever rolled higher is the winner of that contest.
</MudText>

<br />
<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">
    Attributes
</MudText>

<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
    Attributes are special Skills that are primarily used and called out by the GM to determine whether a character can resist or persist through an effect they were exposed to.
    <br />
    <br />
    All Skills are split into five groups of Attributes. It is said that a Skill “contributes” to the Attribute it is assigned to.
    <br />
    <br />
    Attributes otherwise functional equal to Skills, except one important distinction: a character cannot invest a Skill Boost in an Attribute. Instead, for every three Skill Boosts in Skills which contribute to a particular Attribute, that Attribute automatically gains a Skill Boost. Certain features may grant a character an ability for a specific Skill to contribute to additional Attributes.
</MudText>

<br />
<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">
    Upper & Lower Hand
</MudText>

<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
    When a feature states that you have Upper Hand on a check or a roll, you roll an additional Proficiency Die and add the result of that roll to your check.
    <br />
    <br />
    When a feature states that you have Lower Hand on a check or a roll, you do not roll Proficiency Die for that check. If you are Inexperienced in the Skill you are rolling with a Lower Hand, you then halve the result.
    <br />
    <br />
    If you have both Upper and Lower Hand at the same time, they negate each other and you don’t roll any additional dice.
</MudText>

